	<div id="comment_top_64154987" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64154987" name="comment_link_64154987" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23191615&amp;cid=64154987" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64154987)" >Short-term problem, long-term benefit.</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64154987" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64154987); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>4</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Eunomion">Eunomion</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Eunomion">( 8640039 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64154987">		
		on Friday January 12, 2024 @11:28PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23191615&amp;cid=64154987">#64154987</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64154987">If you lure a scientist with a big payday, even if the work they do for the company has little public benefit, they'll fund their own projects later.  And meanwhile they'll be making professional and financial associations that they normally wouldn't, which will advance their work.
<br>
<br>
And nothing stops them from going back to academia, teaching about their experiences in both contexts.
<br>
<br>
People should try to seek a diversity of skills.</div>
	</div>

